<h2>Indiana Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>Indiana offers several attractive incentives for solar panel installations and HVAC system upgrades that significantly improve project economics. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations through 2032, allowing homeowners to deduct 30% of their total solar system cost from their federal taxes. This incentive applies to all system components, including panels, inverters, mounting equipment, and installation labor, making it one of the most valuable solar incentives available.</p>

<p>The state of Indiana provides a property tax exemption for solar energy systems, meaning that the added value of a solar installation does not increase property tax assessments. This exemption applies to both residential and commercial solar installations and remains in effect for the life of the solar system. Additionally, Indiana has no state sales tax on solar equipment, further reducing the upfront cost of solar installations.</p>

<p>Duke Energy Indiana, the state's largest utility, offers net metering programs that credit solar customers for excess electricity generated by their systems. Under net metering, customers receive retail rate credits for surplus solar production that is fed back into the grid, effectively running their electric meter backwards during periods of high solar generation. Duke Energy also provides interconnection services and has streamlined applications for residential solar installations under 25kW.</p>

<p>For HVAC systems, Indiana participates in federal tax credit programs for high-efficiency heat pumps and other qualifying equipment. The Inflation Reduction Act provides tax credits up to \$2,000 for qualifying heat pump installations, while additional rebates may be available through utility efficiency programs. Some local utilities offer rebates for high-efficiency HVAC equipment upgrades, and financing programs are available through various state and utility programs to help homeowners manage upfront costs.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="space-y-6 my-6">
